"Frisa Valtellinese" is an indigenous breed of goat from Valtellina valley in the central Alps in northern Italy. Because of its considerable size, high twinning rate, good maternal ability, high live weight at birth and fast growth of the kids, the prevailing attitude of the breed is the production of meat. Hind legs of these goats are used to produce the Violino, a traditional goat ham from Valtellina and Valchiavenna. Milk production is also noticeable.

"Garfagnina" breed takes its name after the mountain area of Garfagnana, in the northern part of Tuscany region in Central Italy. Morphology of the breed is higly variable in size, coat color, hair lenght, and horns.

"Garganica" breed originated from the Gargano promontory, part of Puglia region in South-East Italy. The breed is medium sized, well known for its hardiness and well suited to difficult habitats, where it lives on range. It is appreciated for milk production.

"Girgentana" breed takes its name from the city of Agrigento. It is a very ancient autochthonous breed from the island of Sicily in South Italy. The most impressive feature of this breed is represented by the large, helical shaped, horns. The most common rearing system is semi-extensive, with the goats grazing in the daylight and housed at night. In bad weather they are held inside and fed with hay. Animals are small sized, however milk production is good and of high-quality.

"Jonica" is an autochthonous breed from gthe province of Taranto, in the southern Italian region of Puglia. Well sized animals, they are held for milk production in traditional family farms for the production of typical cheese ("Cacioricotte" and "Canestrato").

"Lariana" or "Di Livo" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the Livo Valley in the Alpine province of Lecco, in North Italy, near the border with Switzerland. Highly variable in morphology, it is mainly held for the production of meat (kids), but it is capable of moderate milk productions. Tipically brought on mountain pastures in summer.

"Maltese" breed takes its name after the Island of Malta, but it likely came from the Middle East. It is mainly bred in Southern Italy, particularly in Sicily and Sardinia islands. Very good milk producer, it stands hot climate and it fits well also in intensive breeding system.
"Messinese" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the province of Messina, in the island of Sicily, in Southern Italy. Very rustic breed, mainly used for the production of milk.
"Murciana" is a dairy breed of goat originally bred in the Murcia province along the Mediterranean coast of southeastern Spain

"Napoletana" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the province of Napoli, in Southern Italy. It is a very rustic breed traditionally held in family farms on the slopes of the volcano Vesuvius.

"Nicastrese" is an indigenous, dual purpose breed of domestic goats from the Calabria region in Southern Italy. It is held for milk production for cheese making, such as Pecorino Crotonese, which is a PDO ( Protected Designation of Origin).

"Orobica" or "Valgerola" is an autochthonous breed from the Gerola valley in the Northern province of Sondrio, in the Alps. The Orobica has a Strong dairy aptitude, the milk is used for the production of typical cheeses such as the "Bitto PDO". The breed is easily recognized by its long and typically shaped horns.

"Passeirer Gebirgsziege" o "Capra della Passiria" is held for the production of kids in the Autonomous Province of Bozen/Bolzano in the Alps, at the border with Austria. The breed shows a high twinning rate and is well suited to mountain pastures.
"Pomellata" is an autochthonous breed of domestic goat from the Campania region in South Italy. It is a very rustic animal held for milk production.

"Roccaverano" is an autochthonous breed of domestic goat from the Langhe hills, in the region of Piemonte in north-western Italy. The milk is used to make cheese. For example, the "Robiola di Roccaverano - PDO" is made by a mixture of cow milk, goat milk and sheep milk. These large sized goats are well adapted to poor pastures.

"Rossa Mediterranea", also known as "Derivata di Siria" is a breed of goat original from the Middle East. Bred in southern Italy (Sicily, Basilicata and Calabria regions) for the production of milk to be used in cheese making. It is raised in small and medium-sized farms, mostly at range during daylight and in stable at night.

"Rustica di Calabria", also known as "Sciara" or "Nera Rustica" or "Capra di Cosenza" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the province of Cosenza in the Calabria region in Southern Italy. Dual purpose breed, it probably received contributions from other Southern breeds.
Other name: Sciara, Nera Rustica, Capra di Cosenza

Description: "Saanen" is an international breed original from Switzerland and nowadays the most widespread goat breed throughout Europe. It takes its name from the Saanental (Saanen valley) in the Bernese province, in the southern part of the Canton of Bern, in western Switzerland. It is a highly productive dairy goat and its milk is used to obtain fresh and aged cheeses, yoghurt and ricotta.

"Sarda" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the island of Sardinia, off the west coast of Italy. Animals are medium built, long-necked and deep-chested; the does have well-developed udders. The breed is particularly hardy and well-suited to be held on range in harsh conditions.

"Sarda Primitiva" is an indigenous breed of domestic goat from the island of Sardinia, off the west coast of Italy. This breed is quite distinct from the better-known Sarda breed. It is used for producing milk for cheese making. These goats are mainly managed with traditional extensive techniques in the province of Nuoro.

"Screziata" breed can be found across the Campania region in South Italy. The origin of the breed is uncertain, but likely related to the Napoletana breed. The breed is used for milk production. The last population data on this breed trace back to 2018.

"Sempione" or "Simplon" is a relic breed of domestic goats from the mountains of Piedmont in North-West Italy. Only very few head survive. Robust, with good development, it was used for meat production.

"Valdostana" is an Italian breed of domestic goat from the Alpine region of Valle d'Aosta in north-western Italy, from which it takes its name. It is characterised by large sabre-shaped horns, useful in the traditional goat-fighting. The animals are bred both for the production of meat and milk to be transformed into cheese.

"Vallesana" is the Italian strain of a Swiss breed from the canton of Valais, in southern Switzerland. Other names of the breed are "Vallese", "Col noir du Valais", "Chèvre des Glaciers", "Walliser Schwarzhalsziege" or "Race de Viège". In England the breed is kown as "Bagot goat". It can be found in the Alps in northern Italy, in the province of Novara. It lives in particularly inaccessible environments.
"Verzaschese" is a Swiss goat breed from the Canton Ticino. In Italy, it is found in the provinces of Varese, Como and Sondrio. It is a rustic breed very resistant to temperature variations.
"Pezzata Mòchena" is a breed of domestic goat native from the Alpine Province of Trento, in North-East Italy. It is a large sized dual purpose goat.
Italian breed originally from the Emilia-Romagna region in Northern Italy. Also known as "Oca di Roma", it is one of the oldest breeds documented in the world. It is very fertile.

Also known as "Oca Padana", it was selected in Veneto (North East Italy) starting from common geese present in the area. It is a rustic breed that adapts well to different breeding conditions. It lays up to 100 eggs per year with an average weight of 120 grams but has a poor aptitude for hatching. Its meat is very tasty and suitable for roasting and also for transformation into sausages or seasoned meats (goose ham and smoked breast).
Also known as "Grigia di Padova" (Paduan Grey), the Paduan goose is an ancient, large sized Italian breed autochthonous from the Veneto region in North-East Italy.

This rare breed was selected in Veneto (North East Italy) by prof. Alessandro Ghigi for the color lilac with reduced pearling of its plumage; the upper parts have very evident blue shades; legs from light grey to pale orange.
This rare breed was selected in Veneto (North East Italy) by prof. Alessandro Ghigi for the color Lavender blue with both full and reduced pearling; legs from light grey to pale orange.

Coming from West Africa, Guinea fowls have been imported in Europe since ancient Greek times. Mainly bred for the production of meat, it can produce up to 200 eggs per year with a very hard, light brown shell. Wild guinea fowls are monogamous: before AI this made their breeding difficult.
Very similar to wild Guinea fowl (Numida meleagris) but much heavier, mostly in females. Commonly held for the production of tasty meat.
Rare breed of uncertain origin. Livery bluish grey (pearl grey) densely pearly; legs generally yellow but also grey-black.

Ancient international breed of Arabian origin. Historically used as a military horse, now it is used in racing for its speed and resistance, and shows for its beauty. The breed was used to create or improve many breeds, starting with the English Thoroughbred. It is one of the most worldwide renowned horse breeds.

The Giara horse is a pony from the island of Sardinia (Western Italy), living free on an higland area known as "Giara". This horses are small but hardy and able to endure unfavorable conditions. They can be tamed and used for riding. This is one of the few italian horse breeds showing no genetc contribution from English Thoroughbred.
The Monterufoli horse is a pony from Cecina Valley, in the province of Pisa, Tuscany. It shows genetic similarities with other breeds of Italian ponies.

Breed/Most common name: Cavallo Agricolo Italiano da Tiro Pesante Rapido
Description: The breed was founded around 1860, after the unification of Italy. Original from North East Italian plains, it was originally intended for military drafting, such as artillery and carriages. Long used for field work, after the mechanization of agriculture the breed turned into meat production thank to its muscle development and its fast growth. Females are also used for the production of mules. Mules are still used to carry wood out of mountain forests.

Anglo-Arab comes from the cross between English Thoroughbred and Arabian horses. The crosses can both be mated among themselves and back-crossed with the two original breeds. However, the percentage of Arabian blood can not be lower than 25 %. In Italy, the breeding of Anglo-Arab is particularly developed in Sardinia Island (West Italy). The horse has a marked aptitude for equestrian sports, mainly for track races and combined competitions.

Bardigiano is a breed of ponies from Emilia Romagna region. Used in the past for wood and field work in difficult areas, today the breed is appreciated for equestrian tourism, both saddled or harnessed.

Maremmano is a breed of horse from the Tuscan Maremma and Northern Lazio on the Italian West coast. Traditionally a sturdy workhorse used to manage livestock on range, it has been selected to become a riding horse with good sport attitudes. Since the beginning of XX Century the breed has been "improved" by contributions from English Thoroughbred

Pentro is an Italian breed from the Province of Isernia, in the Southern Molise region. The breed was made between the two World wars by crossing a number of Italian breeds. Today the breed is mainly held on range and used for meat production and for equestrian tourism.
This breed is very similar and it shares its genome with the "Maremmano" breed. The breed was recognized in 2010 as an independent population from Lazio region.
Autochthonous from Sicily, the breed is the result of repeated crosses of local mares with stallions from other breeds, particularly Oriental horses.

Cavallo del Catria is an autochthonous breed from the mountains of Pesaro, Ancona and Perugia provinces in central Italy. Originally used in the charcoal production, the breed received genetic contributions by the Maremmano horse. In order to improve its attitude for meat production, in recent years the breed has been crossed with the French breed Franches Montagnes. The breed is genetically very close to the "Cavallo Appenninico".
The breed is a strain of the French pony "Camargue", imported in Italy since 1970. It lives on range over the delta of river Po. It is used for trekking.

The breed comes from the area of Mount Ventasso, in the province of Reggio Emilia, in North Italy. The area was renowned for horse production since the XVIII Century. Since then, it was "improved" by English Thoroughbred and extensively crossed with Maremmano horses. The breed is genetically very close to the "Cavallo Maremmano". Country horse, rustic, resistant and frugal.

Original from Avelengo/Hafling in the autonomous alpine Province of Bolzano/Bozen, it is also known by the Italian name "Avelignese", Haflinger is a pony, typically chestnut with blond mane and tail. Used in the past for field work, the breed has been improved by arabian stallions at the end of XIX century and it has undergone an effective selection in the last 40 years. Today it is used in many Countries for equestrian sports and trekking.
Knabstrupper is a Danish breed of warmblood horse. Mainly used for riding, but also for driving. Typically spot coated, due to a genetic complex called the "leopard complex".

Originated in 1580 in the Habsburg owned stud of Lipizza, now in Slovenia. As we know it today, the breed was founded in the second half of XVI19 II Century, when pedigree information trace back. Basically made by Spanish and Arabian horses, it received contributions from different European Studs, mostly of Spanish origin. The genetic contribution of English Thoroughbred is negligible. Typical baroque horse, the Lipizzans have very elegant gaites and excellent rideability . Their hairs turn white at the age of 4-6 years. Recessive black coated lines also exist. Italy was given an half of the original herd on July 1919. On December 2, 2022, UNESCO inscribed the "Tradition of Lipizzan breeding" in the list of Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.

Murgese horse is native from the Puglia region (Southern Italy). Historically used for field work and transportation, it has undergone selection for sport riding. Saddle horse, due to its robustness and its lively but docile character, it is also used for equestrian tourism and sport.

From the XV throughout the XVII Century the Neapolitan, a breed of Spanish origin, was very well known and bred in most European Studs. The "Napoletano" is an attempt to reconstruct the breed starting from local mares and black Lipizzan stallions. Today the breed is genetically very close to the "Cavallo Maremmano". The morphological conformation is typically "baroque".

Noriker Horse is an Austrian heavy breed of draft horses. Noriker is considered to be native from the central Alpine regions. Mountain breed, used for heavy and slow drafting, very reliable, resistant, robust, and fertile. The breed carries the "leopard complex" and some horses are spot coated.

Original from a military stud in the past Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (South Italy), the breed was dispersed by the Italian Government in 1874. Later, at the beginning of the XX Century, the Italian Army reconstructed the breed on an Anglo-Arab basis. Then, also English Thoroughbred was largely used on the breed. Today the breed is genetically very close to the "Salernitano". It is a saddle horse, used in sports.

The Esperia pony is an autochthonous breed from the mountains of the Province of Frosinone, in Lazio, Central West Italy. The breed was improved by Arabian contributions in the XIX Century. Very robust animals, well adapted to the poor environment they live in.

The origin of English Thoroughbred goes back to the XVIII Century in England, where three Arabian Stalions were mated to local mares in order to obtain racing horses. Since then the English Thoroughbred spread over the entire World, everywhere changing equestrian uses and traditions. Overtime, the English Thoroughbred has been used to "improve" most horse breeds.

Purebred Oriental (PSO) is a horse breed of ancient Arabian origin developed in Sicily (South Italy). The Studbook was officially recognized by the former Kingdom of Italy with Royal Decree No. 2690 on September 19, 1875. It is a strain of arabian horse.

Autochthonous from the Southern province of Salerno, in Campania, the Salernitano breed is the result of repeated crosses of local mares with English Thoroughbred. The breed is genetically very close to the "Persano" horse.

Autochthonous from the Nebrodi Montains, in the province of Messina, in Eastern Sicily, the breed is the result of repeated crosses of local mares with stallions from other breeds, particularly the "Maremmano" horse.
Small sized horses from the province of Nuoro, in the island of Sardinia. Genetically close to other Italian pony breeds, it shows clear components of Spanish and Arabian derivation.

Sella Italiano has developed over time from traditional italian saddle horse populations improved by crosses with other European saddle breeds, English Thoroughbred, Maremmano, Persano and Salernitano. These crosses are still ongoing. Sella Italiano is the main horse population in Italy for show jumping.

Tolfetano actually is a strain of the original Maremmano breed remained more suitable for work on horseback. Genetically different from the Maremmano for the minor contribution by English Thoroughbred.

Starting from the second half of the XIX Century the Italian Trotter was developed with contributions by Russian, French and North American horses. Today, champions from all over the World appear in the pedigrees of Italian trotters. Italian trotters are used for harness racing with sulkies.

The breed is a strain of the French breed "Frances Montagnes", imported in Italy since 1980. It lives in the Mountains between Emilia and Tuscany regions, in North-Central Italy. It is used for trekking.
Original from the French Pyrenees, it has been imported in North-East Italy, at the border with France. Used in the past for mining work, today it is used for trekking.

Apulo-Calabrese is a population of black domestic pig living in the Southern Apennines, from Lazio to Puglia and Calabria Regions. It takes different local names across the wide area of diffusion. Believed to be an ancient breed used in transhumance, it thrives in outdoor farming. Meat is used in traditional salami making: capocollo, lard, bacon, ham, sausage and soppressata.
Other name: Calabrese , Nero calabrese , Pugliese , Nero pugliese , Nero dei Monti Dauni meridionali , Nero di Capitanata, Nero lucano , Nero abruzzese , Nero reatino , Nero dei Monti Lepini , Nero maremmano

Description: Casertana is an autochthonous breed of small sized breed, of slate dark grey color. Two characteristics of this breed are quite unique: it is mostly hairless and it carries wattles. Traditionally held in family styes, it is renowed for the quality of its meat.

Cinta Senese is a breed of pigs from Tuscany region, in Central Italy. Since 2006, animals raised in Tuscany have PDO status, and their meat is named "Cinta Senese PDO". It is a rustic and frugal breed, suitable for continuous outdoor breeding. Cinta Senese produces excellent meat of excellent quality for the transformation into typical products. The coat is typically black with a white belt around the chest.
Other name: Cinta , Cinto , Cinto toscano , Cinturello umbro , Cinturino umbro

Description: Italian Duroc has been specifically selected to improve the suitability of meat to seasoning, mostly by reducing weight losses of meat in brine and by maintaining sufficient fat coverage. However, the breed is highly productive under intensive farming systems. Typically the animals are red coated, but a dominant white variant exists. The breed is mainly used for the production of crosses for the production of typical PDO cured meats such as Parma and San Daniele hams.

Italian Landrace has been specifically selected to improve the suitability of meat to seasoning, mostly by reducing weight losses of meat in brine and by maintaining sufficient fat coverage. However, the breed has excellent reproductive performances under intensive farming systems. The breed is mainly used for the production of dams of pigs for typical PDO cured meats such as Parma and San Daniele hams.

Italian Large White, or Italian Yorkshire, has been specifically selected to improve the suitability of meat to seasoning, mostly by reducing weight losses of meat in brine and by maintaining sufficient fat coverage. However, the breed has excellent productive and reproductive performances under intensive farming systems. The breed is mainly used for the production of dams of pigs for typical PDO cured meats such as Parma and San Daniele hams.

Mora Romagnola is an autochthonous breed of pigs from Emilia-Romagna region, in northern Italy. it is a large breed, with strong skeletal structure. Nearly extinct at the beginning of XXI Century, it has expanded thanks to an effective conservation program. It is currently used for gourmet salami products.
Other name: Bruna romagnola, Castagnina, Forlivese, Bolognese , Faentina, Mora

Description: Nero Siciliano is a breed of pigs from the Mediterranean island of Sicily, in southern Italy. Precocious and long-lived breed, it is characterized by good fertility, strong resistance to diseases and climatic adversities. Capable to make the most out of poor foods, its meat is mainly used for handcrafted cured meat.
Other name: Nero delle Madonie, Nero dell’Etna, Nero dei Nebrodi, Nero ibleo

Description: Nero di Lomellina is a new breed started in 2005 from a farm in the province of Pavia, in Northern Italy. The original herd received genetic contributions by Cinta Senese, Mora Romagnola and Apulo Calabrese breeds. The genetic program tries to reproduce the characteristic of two extinct Piedmontese breed: the "Cavour" and the "Garlasco".
Other name: Nero di Piemonte, Nero piemontese, Nero di Cavour

Description: Nero di Parma is a new breed of pig started during the 90's of last Century in the province of Parma, in Emilia-Romagna region. The breed was re-constructed by crossing Cinta Senese, Mora Romagnola, Casertana and Large Black breeds. Since 2006 the herdbook is closed to introductions from other breeds. The genetic programs aims to produce heavy pigs for the transformation in high quality typical products.

Pietrain is a Belgian breed of pig. Its meat is excellent for butchery but not very suitable for seasoning, even after the complete eradication of the gene responsible for PSE (Pale, Soft, Exudative meat). The breed is hardly used in Italy any longer.

Sarda is a breed of domestic pig from the Mediterranean island of Sardinia, Italy. Sarda pigs are almost exclusively held outdoors: pigs are free to graze in the mountain wooded areas, where they feed on acorns, chestnuts and roots. Sardinian breed pigs are mainly used for the production of weaned piglets to roast.
Romagnolo is a large sized breed of pigeon from Romagna, a region in North-East Italy. It probably derives from an ancient breed known as "Colombo Ascolano". It is only bred for its looks.
Sottobanca Modenese is a large sized breed of pigeon from the Province of Modena, a city in north Italy. It used to be bred in rural households for meat production.

Very ancient breed of pigeons from the Province of Modena, a city in north Italy. Bred since the XIV Century as a messenger, it possibly comes from crosses between local pigeons and eastern breeds. Very fast and agile flyer, it shows over 200 different plumages
Despite its name, the Alaska Rabbit originated in Germany. It is a medium-sized rabbit breed, weighing 3 – 4 kg with glossy black fur.

Angora is a special breed used for its fur, harvested by combing the rabbits. The breed likely originated in Ankara (historically Angora), the capital city of Turkey.The breed became well known in the XVIII Century in France. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 3.5 - 4 Kg.

Known as "Silver Grand", it is one of the oldest recorded breed of domestic rabbit, dating back at least to the XVI Century.The fur is one of the most typical feature of this breed: it is extremely dense and 3,8 to 5,0 cm in length. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.5 - 5 Kg.

Selected out of the French breed "Argentata di Champagne", Argentata italiana underwent a genetic improvement program for productive performance designed for meat production under intensive conditions. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4 - 4.7 Kg.

Known as "Mini Silver", the breed was first discovered and brought to Europe in the XVI Century. It is a smaller version of "Argentata Grande" but it dies not have the rich fur of the larger breed. It is a light breed, weighing 2.7 - 3 Kg.

The "Argente du Champagne", also known as "Le Riche" because of its typical, rich, silver coat. It is an old breed, mentioned by Charles Darwin to exemplify the evolution of coat silvering in black born rabbits. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.5 - 5 Kg.

Also known as "Lop", the Italian Ariete directly derives from the "Ariete Inglese". It shows typical droopy ears and very prominent forehead and mandible. It is a giant breed, not very mobile, weighing over 5 Kg.

Known as "Dwarf lop", it comes from crosses started in 1949 between the French Lop (one of the larger lop breeds) with a tiny Netherland Dwarf by a Dutch rabbit breeder. It is a light breed, weighing 1.5 Kg.

Also known as "Mini Lop", this breed was selected in Germany starting from crosses between "Ariete Inglese" and "Chincilla". Initially the breed was known as "Klein Widder" and it was recognized in 1964. It is a light breed, weighing 3 - 3.25 Kg.

Also known as "English Lop" or "Belier Anglais", it was the first breed to show droopy ears and prominent forehead and mandible. Charles Darwin studied the “Large Lop—Eared Rabbits” in “The Variation of Animals and Plants under Domestication” first published in 1869. It was the first rabbit breed held as a pet. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.75 - 5 Kg.

The breed was first selected at the end of the XIX Century in The Netherland. It was named "Havana" due to its resemblance to the homonym cigar. Likely derived from the "Olandese" breed. It is a light breed, weighing 2.7 - 3 Kg

Selected out of the American breed "Bianca di nuova Zelanda", Bianca italiana underwent a genetic improvement program for productive and reproductive performance designed for meat production under intensive conditions. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 3.5 - 4.5 Kg.

The "New Zealand White" was the first breed developed in 1910 in the United States for meat production. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.3 - 4.7 Kg. Together with the Californian, the New Zealand White is the most widespread breed for meat production.

The two varieties "Vienna White" and "Vienna Blue" were created for meat and fur production by crossing the Flemish Giant with other Eastern European breeds and first shown at an exhibition in Austria at the end of the 19th century. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4 - 4.3 Kg.

The two varieties "Vienna Blue" and "Vienna White" were created for meat and fur production by crossing the Flemish Giant with other Eastern European breeds and first shown at an exhibition in Austria at the end of the 19th century. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4 - 5 Kg.

The "Californian", also known as "California White", is a breed of rabbit originally developed for fur and meat production in Lynwood, CA, in 1923 by crossing American Chinchilla with Russian breeds first and then with New Zealand White. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4 - 4.3 Kg. Together with the New Zealand White, the Californian is the most widespread breed for meat production.
Known as "Giant Chinchilla", iIt was formed in Missouri (USA) around 1921 by crossbreeding Chinchilla rabbit and New Zealand white rabbit. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.5 -5 Kg.

Known as "Chinchilla", It was shown for the first time on April 1913 at Saint-Maur, in France and it was considered the ideal fur rabbit, greatly resembling the South American Chinchilla lanigera. It is a light breed, weighing 2.5 - 2.75 Kg.

First formed in England in 1889, It was originally known as "Polish rabbit" and then called "Ermine" due to similarity to white ermine species. It was the first light breed to be selected, weighing only 1.2 - 1.5 Kg.
Known as "Fairy Pearly", it originated in Germany in the XX Century by crossing "Avana" and "Fata di Marburgo" breeds. Quite uncommon, it is a light breed, weighing 2.5-2.75 Kg.

Known as "Fairy Marburg", it originated in Germany around 1912, when a young rabbit with a 'wrong' grey color from a litter of "Avana" rabbits was offered to the concierge of a school. It aroused interest in 1915 at a rabbit fair and it was finally recognized as a breed. It is a light breed, weighing 2.75 - 3 Kg.
Known as "Black and Tan", it was obtained by crosses among domestic and wild rabbits in late XIX Century. It is an amateur light breed, weighing 2.5 - 3 Kg.

Known as "Fauve de Bourgogne", this breed comes from the selection of fawn rabbits out of the local population in Burgundy at the beginning of XX Century. It is also used as the male line for intensive meat production. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.2 - 4.7 Kg.

It was exhibited for the first time in France in 1887 and arrived in USA in 1920. It is also known as "Harlequin rabbit" for its typical black and yellow coat. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 3.5 -4 Kg.

Also known as "Bristle White", this breed was selected at the beginning of XX Century as a variant of "Chinchilla" and it was recognized as a breed at a 1928 Berlin fair. Quite uncommon, it is a light breed, weighing around 3.5 kg.

Original from Patagonia, the breed has been improved in the Flanders (Belgium). For this reason It is also known as "Flemish Giant". The first standard for this breed was written in 1893. It is a very heavy breed, weighing up to 8 Kg and over.

In 1906 the Giant White breed was created in France in the Department of Gironde in Aquitaine. It was the result of crossbreeding among Angora, Argent du Champagne and Flemish Giant breeds. Originally named "Géant blanc du Bouscat" (the village of origin), the first standard was established in 1924. It is a heavy breed, weighing up to 7 Kg and over.

The breed first appeared in early '900 in the Lorraine French region. Together with the Giant and the White Giant, the Checkered Giant, also known as "Geant Papillon Français", is one of the largest breeds of rabbits, weighing up to 7 Kg.

Also known as “Grigio Piemontese“, the breed has been recently recognized out of a population of grey rabbits widespread in Piedmont region in North West Italy. These rabbits were very common until the ‘50s of last Century, to become rarer in recent years. The recognition of the breed allowed to establish a preservation program. It is a medium-sized rabbit breed, weighing 3 – 5,5 kg with grey fur.

This breed was selected out of the "Geant Papillon Français" in the French village of Totot-en-Auge, in Calvados, Normandy, and it was officially recognized in 1922. It is a medium size breed, weighing 4 - 4.5 Kg, with an excellent attitude for meat production.

It was selected in the XIX Century in Belgium, where it was named "Lievre Belge". These rabbits remind the wild hare for their red fur, long legs and thin and elongated body: features that make them look very different from other domestic rabbits. It is a medium size breed, weighing 3.7 - 4.2 Kg.

The breed was developed in the 80's at the University of Viterbo, in Italy, for the needs of family farms. Long legs, elongated body and long ears justify its name. It is a medium size breed, weighing 3.5 - 5 Kg.

Known as "Lynx", it originates from Germany and was created by crossing "Focata" and "Fata di Marburgo". The breed was first exhibited in Düsseldorf 1919. Characterized by a very typical "violet" color, it is a light breed, weighing 2.5 - 3 Kg.

Selected out of the American breed "Californiana", Macchiata italiana underwent a genetic improvement program for productive and reproductive performance designed for meat production under intensive conditions. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 3.0 - 4.0 Kg.

Also known as "Marten", these rabbits were recognized as a breed in 1940. The breed is the result of crosses of "Chinchilla" with Himalayan and Armenian rabbits. It is a light breed weighin 2.7 - 3.2 Kg, with thick and beautiful fur.

Also known as "Coloured Dwarfs" the breed was first produced in the Netherlands in the early 20th century by crossing between Polish rabbits and small wild rabbits. Identical to the "Ermellino" breed but for the fur, that can have any solid color. It is a very light breed, weighing less than 1,2 Kg.

The "Dutch" rabbit originated in the Flanders, and was later selected in England. Originally known as the "Petit Brabançon" from Brabant province, it shows a vey typical fur, white in front and colored in the back. It is a light breed, weighing 2.5 - 3 Kg.

Also know as "Gold Saxony", its original name was Sachsenngold rabbit, originated from Rohrdorf, Germany and selected in 1925. The rabbit was first shown in 1952 and its color is intense red. It is a light breed weighing 2.5 - 3.5 Kg.
The "English Spot" was selected out of the "Gigante Pezzato" at the end of XIX Century and it and was named "English spot" in 1924. It is a light breed, weighing 2.5 - 3 Kg.
The "Small Spot" was obtained by crossing "Gigante Pezzato" and "Pezzata Inglese". It was recognized as "Petit Papillon" in France in 1984. It is a light breed weighing 2.5 - 3.5 Kg.

Selected in Germany in early XX Century, the breed black and yellow pied on a white fur. After the first exports from Germany to the US in 1923, it was recognized as a breed in the US. It is a medium sized breed weighing around 3.5 Kg.

This special breed originated in France in 1919. The rabbits have a short and thick fur, similar to velvet. Since the beginning, it has undergone an intense selection for a variety of colors by fanciers and the fur industry. It is medium sized, weighing 3 - 5 Kg.

The "New Zealand Red" was selected in California where it arrived from New Zealand together with the "New Zealand White" around 1910. It was introduced in American standard in 1916. In Italy the White and Red New Zealand are considered different breeds. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 4.0 - 4.3 Kg.

It is a very ancient rabbit breed, likely of Asian origins. It was described for the first time in France in 1854 and studied in England by Charles Darwin who described it as "Moscow hymalayan rabbit" with snow white fur excepting ears, nose and tarsi. Its typical fur was inherited by the "California" breed. It is a light breed, weighing around 2.5 Kg.

This special breed is the result of a mutation appeared in an "Havana" rabbit in Pendleton, IN, USA around 1940. The mutation made the hair very thin and bright. It is a light breed, weighing less than 3.5 Kg.

It was developed in the state of Thuringia in Germany, likely from a mix of Himalayan, "Argentato di Champagne", and "Gigante" breeds. The breed was first recognized in Germany in 1907. It is a medium sized breed, weighing 3.5 - 4 Kg.

Also known as "Fox", this special breed was founded in Switzerland probably by crossing "Angora", "Cincilla", "Avana" and maybe "Ermellino" breeds. The breed has been recognized in Germany since 1962. The fur is very thick but not as productive as that of Angora rabbits. It is a light breed weighing little over 3.0 Kg.

Alpagota is a medium sized, alpine sheep breed autochthonous from the province of Belluno in the Veneto region in North-East Italy. Ewes are milked, and therefore most lambs are slaughtered at weaning. The meat of Alpagota lambs is very appreciated. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Also known as "Moscia" or "delle Murge", the Altamurana is a medium sized, autochthonous sheep breed from Puglia region in Southern Italy. Traditionally held for the production of milk, weaned lambs and wool. The name "Moscia" refers to its slightly ruffled and drooping fleece. Both rams and ewes are short horned.

Appenninica is an autochthonous, medium sized sheep breed from Tuscany and Umbria regions, in Central Italy. The Appenninica is bred for the production of lambs slaughtered between 15 and 30 Kg live weight. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.
Assaf is a large sized international sheep breed developed in Israel in the 50's of last Century. It is a highly productive dairy breed selected for intensive farming. Only few rams show small horns.

Bagnolese is a medium to large sized sheep breed, autochthonous from the province of Avellino, in Campania region in South Italy. It is a dual purpose breed capable of producing milk with high protein content, suitable for the production of cheeses. Males carry strong horns.

Barbaresca is a medium-large sized sheep breed from the island of Sicily in South Italy. It is a dual purpose breed derived from ancient crosses of "Pinzirita" with North African sheep. It is a dual purpose breed living on poor in hot climate. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Bergamasca is a large sized autochthonous sheep breed from the province of Bergamo, in Lombardy, in Northern Italy. The breed is used for the production of heavy lambs mainly under transhumance farming systems. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Berrichon du Cher is a medium sized French sheep breed. Precocious, robust and prolific, it is bred for the production of wool and lambs. The breed has not shown a good adaptation to the Italian conditions. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Biellese takes its name from the city of Biella, in Piedmont region, in North West Italy. Large sized, It is mainly bred for the production of heavy lambs mainly under transhumance farming systems. Similar to the Bergamasca breed, neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Brentegana is an Italian sheep breed originated in the Province of Verona in Northern Italy. It is a dual purpose breed, meat and wool, usually taken to mountain pastures in summer. Neither rams nor ewes have horns. The last population data on this breed trace back to 2018.

Brianzola is a large sized sheep breed original from Lombardy region in Northern Italy. Similar to "Bergamasca" and "Biellese", it is held for meat production. Twinning is common and neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Brigasca is a medium-large sized sheep breed original from Liguria region in North West Italy at the border with France. Very rustic, mostly farmed for the production of weaned lambs. Most animals, males and females, carry horns.

Brogne, or Brogna, is a medium sized sheep breed original from a very specific area (Lessinia) in the Veneto region in North East Italy. This breed is mainly held for the production of lamb meat. Some rams show vestiges of horns.

Ciavenasca is a relic breed of small-sized sheep from two alpine valleys in Lombardy region in North Italy. The production consists in weaned lambs. Neither rams nor ewes have horns. The last population data on this breed trace back to 2018.

Ciuta is a relic breed of small-sized sheep autochthonous from the "Masino" Valley, in the northern province of Sondrio, Lombardy region, at the border with Switzerland. It is a small sized breed held for meat production on very poor montain pastures. Few animals survive in the area of origin. Both males and felemale carry horns.

Comisana is an Italian breed of medium-large sized sheep important for their milk production. Original from the Southern Island of Sicily, it is also known as "Lentinese", from the town of Lentini in the Province of Siracusaù. Likely derived from ancient crosses among mediterranean breeds, it currently undergoes an innovative "in-nucleus" selection program for milk production. Neither rams nor ewes have horns.

Cornella Bianca is a large sized sheep breed original from the provinces of Bologna and Ferrara. The breed used to be held in lowland farms for the supplementary production of milk and meat in marginal areas. Nowadays the breed is quite rare. Both rams and ewes carry horns.

"Cornigliese" is a large size breed created in the XVIII Century in the Province of Parma in Northern Italy by crossing local breeds with Merinos from Spain. It takes its name from the town of Corniglio, in the Apennines mountains. The breed is mainly held for meat but also its milk and wool productions are interesting. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Dell’Amiata is a medium-sized breed of sheep autochthonous from the provinces of Grosseto and Siena, on the slopes of Mount Amiata in Tuscany. Originated by crossing local populations with Merinos sheep, it is known mainly held for meat production. The majority of rams carry horns while most ewes don't.

Delle Langhe is a large-sized sheep breed autochthonous from the province of Cuneo, in Piedmont region in Northwest Italy . It is an excellent milk producer and for this reason, it spread also outside the area of origin. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Fabrianese takes its name from the city of Fabriano, in Ancona province, in the Central-Eastern region of Marche. It is a large sized breed with influences by the Bergamasca breed. It is mainly held for meat production. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Finarda, also known as "Finarola", is a large sized breed obtained by crossing "Bergamasca" and "Biellese", in the same areas of origin of these two founder breeds. Today the "Finarda" is recognized as a relic breed, only used for meat production. Neither rams nor ewes have horns. The last population data on this breed trace back to 2018.

Frabosana is medum-sized sheep breed autochthonous from the Mountains in the province of Cuneo. Very rustic and capable to make the most out of poor mountain pastures, the "Frabosana" used to be milked but it suffered the competition by the more productive "Delle Langhe" breed. Both rams and ewes carry horns.

Frisona is large-sized breed original from Eastern Friesland in Germany. Known as Ostfriesisches Milchschaf (Ger.) or Fries melkshaap (Ned.), it is an excellent milk producer. Repeatedly imported in Italy, it suffered the harsher mediteranean conditions. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Garessina is a small-sized breed from the province of Cuneo, in the Piedmont region in northwest Italy. Usually held in mountain farms, nowadays it is mainly used for milk production, but traditionally it was also important for wool. Neither rams nor ewes are horned.

Garfagnina Bianca is a small-sized sheep breed original from the Garfagnana area in the province of Lucca, in Tuscany Region. Mainly held for milk production, it resembles the "Massese" breed for the important, spiral-shaped horns shown by both males and females.

Gentile di Puglia is a medium-sized sheep breed originated in the XV Century in Southern Italy, in the region of Puglia by crosses of local populations with Spanish Merinos breeds. Notwithstanding the high quality of its wool. Currently, the breed is mainly held for meat production. Only rams carry horns while ewes are polled.
Ile-de-France is a large-sized sheep breed original from France and internationally spread. Excellent producer of heavy leambs, it also is a good producer of wool. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.

Istriana is a medium-sized breed of sheep from the Karst area across Nort-East Italy, Slovenia and Croatia. Likely a mixture of mediterranean and balkanic populations, it is mainly held for milk production. It is a merinized breed, all rams and most ewes carry horns.

Juraschaf is a medium-sized sheep breed originated from the Jura massif in Switzerland since the XIV Century. The original Swiss name is "Schwarzbraunes Bergschaf", but in Italy it is known as "Juraschaf", while the name "Schwarzbraunes Bergschaft" is used for a breed known in Austria as "Braunes Bergschaft". The breed is held in the alpine Province of Bolzano (Bozen) for its triple attitude: milk, wool and lamb meat. The breed is hornless.

Lacaune is a French breed of medium-sized sheep originated in the Occitania region, in Southern France. The breed has been intensively selected for milk production and it has internationally widespread. The milk of Lacaune has high butterfat and protein contents and it is used for producing famous cheeses. The breed has been imported in Italy where it encountered some adaptation difficulties. The Lacaune is hornless.

Lamon is a large-sized sheep breed autochthonous from few communities of the province of Belluno, Veneto region in northeastern Italy. It is still held for the production of meat on poor mountain pastures, but the breed is severely endangered. The breed is hornless.

Leccese, also known as "Moscia Leccese" is a medium-sized breed of sheep that takes its name from the city of Lecce, in the southern end of Puglia region in Southern Italy. It is mainly kept in Puglia and Basilicata regions for milk production. Rams are spiral horned while ewes are polled.

Marrana is a large-sized breed of sheep once bred on the Apennines across the regions Liguria and Emilia-Romagna. Similar to the "Bergamasca" and "Biellese" breeds, this polled breed used to be held for the production of lamb meat. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.

Massese is a medium-sized Italian sheep breed, not very common but important for milk production. It owes its name to the city of Massa, in Tuscany region. It currently undergoes an innovative "in-nucleus" selection program for milk production. The breed has a quite peculiar look, with a brown-black coat and well developed horns, both in rams and in ewes.

The Matesina is a large-sized sheep breed from the province of Caserta, in Campania region, Southern Italy. Likely a variant of the "Gentile di Puglia", the Matesina is a dual purpose breed (wool and meat). Rams carry horns while ewes don't. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.

Merinizzata Italiana is a large-sized sheep breed from Central-Southern Italy. The breed was obtained by crossing native merinized breeds "Gentile di Puglia" and "Sopravissana" with imported Merino breeds such as the French "Berrichon du Cher", "Île-de-France", and the German "Merinolandschaf". The goal was to produce a good dual purpose breed (wool and meat). The breed is hornless.

Nera di Arbus, is a small-sized sheep breed from the Island of Sardinia, West-Italy. Recently recognized as an independent breed, it is similar to the "Sarda" breed, but its fleece is black. Traditionally bred for its dark colored wool, ewes are also milked. Both rams and ewes have horns.

Nostrana is a medium-sized population of sheep original from the Apennines across the regions Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna. Most likely related to the "Garfagnina bianca" breed, it is a dual purpose breed (wool and meat). The breed is mostly hornless. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.

Noticiana is a medium-sized sheep breed that takes its name from the city of Noto, in Siracusa Province, in Sicily. Likely a variant of Comisana breed, it is mainly held for its capability of producing milk from very harsh and arid pastures. The breed is generally hornless and it can have wattles.

Pecora di Corteno is a medium-sized sheep breed that owes its name to the town of Corteno Golgi, in the Alpine valley Valcamonica, Province of Brescia, Lombardy Region. it is mainly held for the production of heavy lambs. The breed is hornless.

The Pinzirita is a small to medium-sized sheep breed autochthonous from the Mediterranean island of Sicily, Italy. The breed is very rustic and it adapts to very difficult environments. It is mainly held for the production of milk. Rams carry horns while ewes are polled.

The Plezzana takes its name from "Plezzo", the italian name of the Slovenian town of Bovec. The breed is also known as "Bovška" in Slovenian and "Krainer Steinschaf" in German. It is a small-sized breed original from the valley of the Isonzo-Soča river. It is a dual-purpose breed very well adapted to mountain pastures and mostly held for milk production. The breed is generally hornless.

Pomarancina probably is a variety of the "Appenninica" breed. It comes from the area of Volterra, in Pisa province, Tuscany region. The breed is medium-sized, hornless, very rustic, and it is held for the production of lamb meat.

Also known as "Nobile di Badia", or "Gadertaler" or "Tauferer", it is a medium-sized breed from the alpine provinces of Bolzano and Belluno. It is a dual purpose breed (wool and lambs) that needs to be kept on pasture all year round. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.
Other name: Pusterese, Tedesca di Pusteria, Val di Pusteria, Pustera Gigante

Description: Quadrella is a small to medium-sized breed of sheep original from the provinces of Benevento and Avellino, in Campania region, South-Italy. it is one of the breeds of the Apennine strain, like the "Laticauda". It is a dual-purpose breed, milk and meat. Rams usually carry horns while ewes are polled.

Romanov is a medium sized Russian breed. Adapted to cold, continental climate, these sheep are held for the production of lamb meat. The breed is renowned for its excellent precocity and prolificacy. Ewes and most rams are polled.

Rosset is an autochthonous, medium sized, breed from the alpine Valle d'Aosta region in north-west Italy. Traditionally held in small farms for all purposes (milk, meat, wool), more recently it has been bred for the production of lambs and some wool. Most ewes and rams are polled.

Saltasassi is an autochthonous, light breed from the province of Novara, in Piedmont region in North West Italy. Its name, meaning "rock jumper", gives an idea of the agility and hardiness of this local breed, held for the production of lambs on hilly and mountain pastures. Both rams and ewes are polled.

Also known as "Demontina", "Sambucana" is an autochthonous, medium sized breed from few valleys in the province of Cuneo in Piedmont region, in North West Italy. It is a very rustic breed mainly held for meat. Usually polled, only few rams carry small horns.

Sampeirina is an autochthonous, medium sized breed from the Sampeyre and Val Varaita valleys in the province of Cuneo, in Piedmont region, North West Italy. Traditionally bred for the production of lambs and wool. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.

Sarda is an autochthonous, medium sized breed from the island of Sardinia, West Italy. By far the most common and economically important sheep breed in Italy, it is very rustic and capable to adapt to different types of farming. Sarda is exclusively bred for milk production for cheese making, mostly "Pecorino Romano" and "Pecorino Sardo", both PDO products. Both ewes and rams are generally polled or they carry rudimentary horns.

Savoiarda is a medium sized breed from the mountain part of the province of Torino, in Piedmont region, North West Italy. Sharing the same environment with the Rosset breed, it is a relic breed held for the production of lambs on very poor pastures. Rams always carry horns while some ewes are polled.

Schwarzbraunes Bergschaf, in Italian "Pecora nero Bruna" was originally obtained by crosses between the "Steinschaf" and the "Bergamasca" breeds in the Tyrol region, across Austria and Italy. In Austria this breed is known as "Braunes Bergschaf", while the original "Schwarzbraunes Bergschaf" is a swiss breed known in Italy as "Juraschaf". This breed is held on alpine pastures in the Autonomous Province of Bolzano-Bozen in North Italy. It is a medium sized, polled, dual purpose breed (meat and wool).

The original name of the Schwarznasenschaf is "Nez noir du Valais". It is a very old breed, documented since the XV Century in the Swiss Canton of Valais. Also known as "Waliser" or, in Italian, "Pecora dal naso nero" or "Vallese". It is a medium-large sized sheep, bred in the Autonomous Province of Bolzano-Bozen in North Italy both for meat and wool. The breed is perfectly adapted to the high mountain environment. Both rams and ewes are horned.

Sciara. also known as "Moscia Calabrese", is a native sheep breed from the provinces of Cosenza and Catanzaro in the Calabria region in Southern Italy. It is a very rustic breed capable of exploiting poor pastures in hot climate. it is held for the production of milk. Small to medium sized breed, generally polled.

Sopravissana originates from crosses of the old "Vissana" breed with "Merinos" rams in the XVIII Century. Original from Marche region, it spread throughout Central Italy. Medium sized, it is mainly held for the production of lambs, even if its wool is of good quality. Rams carry horns while ewes are polled.

Tacola is a large-sized breed native from the mountains of Piedmont, in Northwest Italy. Like the very similar breed "Biellese", it is held for the production of lambs mainly under transhumance farming systems. it is a very rustic, polled breed suitable for the mountain environment.
Texel is a Dutch breed original from the island of Texel and intensively selected for meat production during the XX Century. The breed is polled, only few head are present in Italy.

Original from the Bavarian Alps in Germany, this breed spread across Tyrol, both in Austria and in Italy. Also known with the Italian name "Pecora delle rocce", it is bred on alpine pastures in the Autonomous Province of Bolzano-Bozen in North Italy. It is a rustic breed, mainly held for the production of meat. Rams are horned while ewes are polled or only show rudimentary horns.

Trimeticcia di Segezia was created in the '70 of the XX Century at the Experimental Institute of the Italian Ministry of Agriculture in Foggia, in Puglia region in South Italy. Half-breeds females "Ile de France" by "Gentile di Puglia" where mated to "Würtemberg" rams. The products were then selected to obtain a triple purpose breed capable to stand the hot climate in South Italy. It is a large breed, completely polled.

Turchessa, also known as "Turchesca" is a relic breed from the slopes of the Vesuvius volcano and now surviving with few animals in the provinces of Benevento and Avellino, in Campania region, in South Itlay. Likely to derive from crosses with North-African breeds, it was mainly bred for milk production. It is rustic, frugal and well adapted to the poor grazing of its mountain environment. Males carry horns while ewes are polled.

Valle del Belice breed is widespread in Sicily, in South Italy. This breed was likely obtained by repeated crosses among "Pinzirita", "Comisana" and "Sarda" breeds. It is a medium-sized breed with good attitude for milk production in hot environment. Rams carry horns while ewes are polled.

Varesina is a large-sized breed similar to the "Bergamasca". It comes from the province of Varese, in the Northern part of Lombardy region, in North Italy. It is held outside all year round for meat production. It is a relic breed. The last population data trace back to 2018.

Also known as "Foza", the "Vicentina" breed originated from the Asiago Plateau, across the Provinces of Vicenza and Trento in North Italy. It is a medium to large-sized breed, quite rare, still held for both meat and wool production in small family farms.

Vilnösser Schaf, in Italian "Tingola" or "Fiemmese" o "Pecora dagli occhiali" was originally obtained by crossing the breeds "Bergamasca" and "Padovana", the latter being now extinct. Bred in the Dolomites area, in the Autonomous Provinces of Bolzano-Bozen and Trento, it is held to produce lambs and wool under vertical transhumance farming systems. Neither rams nor ewes carry horns.
Other name: Villnösser Brillenschaf, Fiemmese, Tingola, Pecora dagli occhiali

Description: This breed takes its name from the municipality of Zeri, in the Tuscany region at the border with the Liguria and Emilia regions. Very rustic breed, held outside all year round, it is a medium sized breed, related to the "Appeninica" and "Massese" breeds, held for meat production. Both sexes carry well developed horns.

Laticauda breed, also known as "Barbaresca Campana," originated from the Provinces of Avellino and Benevento, in Campania region in South Italy, from crosses among local and North-African sheep. The breed is large-sized, dual purpose breed (milk and meat), and it is traditionally held in small, family farms. This breed is polled.

Schnalserschaf, also known as "Ultnerschaf" or, in Italian, "Pecora della Val Senales" or "Pecora di Val d'Ultimo" is a large sized breed taking its name form the municipality of Senales-Schnals in the Autonomous province of Bolzano-Bozen in North Italy. Most likely the breed derives from the "Bergamasca" breed. It is a dual-purpose breed, raised on alpine pastures to produce meat and wool. Both rams and ewes are polled.
Other name: Pecora della Val Senales, Pecora di Val d'Ultimo, Ultnerschaf

Description: Suffolk is a large-sized British breed. Obtained in the XIX Century by crossing "Norfolk Horn" and "Southdown" breeds. Excellent meat producer, it needs fertile pastures: perhaps for this reason the Italian Suffolk population has never developed much. Both sexes are polled.

Like the "Schwarzbraunes Bergschaf", the "Tiroler Bergschaf", in Italian "Pecora alpina Tirolese", was originally obtained by crosses between the "Steinschaf" and the "Bergamasca" breeds. Tiroler Bergschaf is a medium sized breed from the Tyrol region across Austria and Italy. it is held to produce lambs and wool under vertical transhumance farming systems. Both rams and ewes are polled.
Original from Lombardy region, this breed is a light weight, good grazer, fast growing and resistant to most common turkey diseases. The female has a high propensity to brood.
Small-sized, rustic breed original from the Veneto region in North-East Italy. Very rare, it is only held at amateur level.
Medium-large sized breed, it was selected around 1960 in Veneto region by an experimental station.
Small sized, rustic breed selected by farmers in the XX Century in Lombardy region for self-consumption.

A small breed original from Romagna in North-East Italy, the "Romagnolo" turkeys are great grazer, rustic, resistant to cold tempertures and to most turkey diseases. Females have excellent maternal attitude.
Parma and Piacenza is an heavy breed of turkeys from the Provinces of Parma and Piacenza, in the Emilia region. The meat is highly regarded for its unique flavor and texture

Bronzato Comune is an ancient, small-sized Venetian breed from northern Italy, widespread locally. The breed shows marked hardiness and excellent attitude for brooding. Females of this breed are used in organic breeding of poultry species as natural "incubators".
Selected in the middle of XX Century, it is a medium-sized, precocious and rustic turkey. Excellent grazer, it adapts very well to outdoor breeding even on poor areas.

Animals must be black , females are acceptible with white markings on the udder and on the underline towards the navel. White markings on the scrotum is permissible in the male. Animals must be broad, deep, blocky , and polled.

Small-sized pig used for non-clinical research in new drug development, toxicity test, organ donor for xenotransplantation research, medical practice training and development of bio-medical technology. ◎ Minipigs are pigs whose characteristics have been improved and established though breeding the small-sized breeds of wild or domesticated pigs over various generations. ◎ They are easy to breed due to their small size and to secure population numbers due to their fecundity. As the organs of minipigs are similar to those of humans in size and they are easily turned into specific pathogen-free animals, the demand and fields for their usage are increasing. ◎ Minipigs are similar to humans genetically, local anatomically and physiologically. ◎ Experimental minipigs should produce offsprings that are similar to their parents in size. If they vary significantly in size and pedigree, and are easily infected, it is difficult to use them in experiments. ◎ A single fertile, germ-free minipig pedigree has been established by choosing a small-sized minipigs strain, developing a pure lineage over decades and managing a population through the sterile management processes.
Other name: Mini pigs, Tea cup pigs, Miniature pigs, Yucatan

They are easy to breed due to their small size and to secure population numbers due to their fecundity. As the organs of minipigs are similar to those of humans in size and they are easily turned into specific pathogen-free animals, the demand and fields for their usage are increasing. It could be more precisely related to the Gascon. Within this brown branch, it is often attached to the fawn branch, and not to the alpine branch. She would then be the descendant of a breed that came from North Africa and arrived in Spain then in the southwest of France with the migration of the Arabs in the 7th century, just like the Parthenese which strongly resembles it, as well as the races nearby (Nantes and maraîchine). Description: Miniature Mediterranean Donkeys originated in the Mediterranean area of Northern Africa in ancient times and more recently from the Islands of Sicily and Sardinia off the west coast of Italy. Over time the distinctions between the two island populations blurred and they are now considered one breed properly called Miniature Mediterranean Donkeys. They are simply referred to as Miniature Donkeys in North America.  Purebred Miniature Donkeys in the Mediterranean area are rapidly disappearing as the small donkeys are being mixed with larger breeds. For this reason, Miniature Donkeys in North America have global genetic value. Fortunately, numbers in the U.S. and Canada are strong and are increasing since the first Miniature Donkeys arrived in the United States in the early 1900's. Within the past ten years the export of Miniature Donkeys to England, France, Germany, the Netherlands, Ireland, New Zealand and Australia has demonstrated the increasing popularity of these versatile, affectionate creatures. In 2014 the MDR now has over 65,500 registered donkeys.  The Miniature Donkey is a compact, well-proportioned animal with a sweet, sociable disposition. At maturity (3 years) it is able to pull a cart or carry a pack as it did in its native Sicily and Sardinia.  The Miniature Donkey community should strive to combine as many positive qualities as possible in each jennet and jack pairing to ensure the progeny will be excellent representatives of the breed.

Crested fowl are pre-eminently show birds. Formerly they were kept utilitarian because they were much larger and heavier then the existing farm-fowl, thus providing larger eggs and more meat. The breed’s typical feature is, of course, the knob on the bird’s cranium. Even at birth it is clearly visible. The larger the knob, the larger the crest. The ideal crest is large and round, but does not cover the eyes. The cock's crest feathers should be narrow like the feathers of the neck and saddle, thus the crest is somewhat flattened at the front and the longest crest feathers will reach as far as the lower end of the wattles. The hen's crest feathers are rounder and shorter, thus enabling the crest to become large, round and serried. The breed has many colours, the crest is always white. Black-crested Whites are the exception but they have never been large in numbers although there is a small enthusiastic group of breeders trying to keep the breed.

Leghorn is the English word for Livorno, the city where this breed must have originated. However, the breed has been brought to the current degree of purity outside its country of origin. Leghorns of different types were selected in various countries, but they all have yellow shanks and white ear-lobes. The Leghorn belongs to the lightweight breeds.  The breed became famous for its exceptional egg laying ability. In the first half of the Twentieth Century it was the national breed in the Netherlands, when about 70% of the commercial poultry stock consisted of Leghorns. In the Fifties, the specially selected egg-producing breeds kept in professional poultry farming were replaced by hybrids. Poultry lovers, however, took over the task of caring for the Leghorn and are still preserving it today for future generations.  The Leghorn is called by names that differ from country to country. In the Netherlands, United States and Great Britain the breed is called Leghorn. In Italy, the country of origin, the breed is called Livorno; Belgium has also adopted the name Livorno which coexists together with the name in use in German speaking countries, which is Italiener (German for ‘Italian’). Since Belgium is also a French-speaking country, the French name “Leghorn type moderne” (Italiener type) is another denomination being used in the country. However, in German speaking countries the name Leghorn is specific for the American Leghorn.  The Dutch type is rather elongated in shape, but also very strong in its appearance. The general appearance is that of a slender bird, with broad shoulders that become progressively narrower towards the tail. The eyes are orange red. The cock’s single comb stands up erect, while the hen’s comb’s blade is lopped and falls over on one side. The rose comb variation is also recognised. The comb spike is protruding backwards. The cock weighs between 2.5 and 3.5 kg, the hen between 2.25 and 2,75 kg. The bantam cock will weigh 700 to 800 g and the bantam hen will be 600 to 700 g. Dutch breed from about 35-40 cm. www.kooikerhondje.nl. Vereniging "Het Nederlandse Kooikerhondje". The Kooikerhondje can be seen in paintings from the 16th and 17th centuries, but didn't become an official, recognized race until June 18, 1966. Unfortunately, by the end of World War II, when dwindling duck stocks left the Kooikerhondje out of a job, the breed almost became extinct. In all it is thought only 25 Kooikerhondjes were left in existence. In 1939 Baroness Van Hardenbroek van Ammerstol decided to resurrect the little Kooikerhondje. For generations, the Kooikerhondje was used in an ingenious method of hunting ducks. The hunter would build a trap called a "Kooi" which consists of a curved ditch leading out from a pond frequented by ducks. Over the ditch an arch of netting is suspended. The result is a pipe through which the ducks could enter but could not see the end of. The Kooikerhondje's job was to lure the ducks far enough down the pipe so the hunter could cut off their retreat and drive them to the trap at the end.

For centuries the goat population in the Netherlands consisted of landrace goats. These goats were sober animals with low production, usually horned and long-haired, in all colors. In the beginning of the 20th century Swiss goats were imported to improve milk and meat production of the landrace goats. The Dutch Toggenburg goat has its history in Drenthe. In this province the local landrace goat was crossed with the Swiss Toggenburg goat. In 1938 the Dutch Toggenburg breed was officially established. Typical is the color of milkchocolate, the pattern and the compact type. In the other provinces of the Netherlands the local landrace goats were crossed with Swiss Saanen goats, that resulted in the Dutch White goat. In the province Zeeland breeders preferred the coloured goat more than the white and this resulted in the Dutch Pied original goat. Only two-coloured animals are accepted (black-white or brown-white) by the breed society. Sometimes the Dutch White goat is used for improvement of the offspring of the Dutch Pied original. In the late 80s of the previous century a tremendous growth in professional dairy goat farming took place in the Netherlands. The majority of the Dutch milk goats is not registered in a herd book, the origin of these Dutch Milkgoat is the Dutch White goat, with a dash of foreign blood (Nubian, Alpine, Saanen). The Dutch Pied goat and the Dutch White goat are in 2024 in one breeding committee: "fokcommissie"https://www.wittegeiten.org/

FPS is the Netherlands' oldest and second largest studbook and has about 12,000 members living in the Netherlands and abroad. At this time there are about 40,000 Friesian horses registered. The Friesian horse is a purebred horse native to the Netherlands. Its roots go far back in time. The Friesian horse was recognized as early as the 13th century, and Friesian horses of today still display definite similarities with their distant ancestors. The breed's long history and a consistent breeding policy have consolidated the specific 'Friesian' characteristics. On this sturdy foundation, the Friesian horse has evolved into what it is today: an imposing presence in every respect.  With its black colour, long mane and full tail, the Friesian is recognizable in an instant. The horse has an elegant build and powerful, elevated gaits. Its character is friendly and graciously spirited. All of these qualities make the Friesian a fine horse that can be used for many different purposes.  The Friesian horse is being successfully – and above all, very enthusiastically – employed in various equestrian sports. The specific Friesian qualities are displayed especially well in driving competitions where they can be seen in action before the gig, in the single horse and pairs classes as well as in the unicorn and show cart categories. Competing for the highest honours, these black horses are making themselves very well known.  The Friesian horse is also a fine dressage horse. Its fine self-carriage, willingness to work and inquisitive nature make it perfect for this branch of the sport. Friesians are now increasingly being seen at national competitions where they are displaying their talents to compete on equal terms with all other horses bred for riding purposes. Friesian horses are just as well represented in driving trials and marathon tests. And, last but certainly not least, one can scarcely imagine a more enjoyable partner as a recreational horse than the Friesian.  After the critical period in the 1960s, the tide has turned and the Friesian horse has done nothing but gain in popularity and appreciation. This year, the number of foals born was around 6000, and this number is increasing every year. These larger numbers are giving the FPS an opportunity to be stricter in its selections and in this way to bring the average quality of the horses' conformation and usefulness to a higher plane. In 2009 about 26000 animals in the Netherlands and about 7000 foals were born each year. In 2017 3656 foals were born.   Schurink, A.; Arts, J.A.J.; Ducro, B.J. (2012) Genetic diversity in the Dutch harness horse population using pedigree Livestock Science 143 (2-3). - p. 270 - 277.

Founded on the famous Gelder type of the past, it is a horse with elegant conformation. The Gelder horse has a well-developed forehand, substantial bone and mass, and impressive, distinct gaits with push and power originating in the hindquarters. Noted for its great versatility, the Gelder horse is suited for work in harness as well as under saddle and is distinguished by its happy attitude and reliable temperament. Has a willing, reliable and honest character; is easy to handle.

Spanish mother studbook ANCCE. That is in the Netherlands covered by www.pre-stamboek.nl. In 2008 about 145 females and 42 matings. In 2020 287 females and 41 foals. THE PRE HORSE. BREED HISTORY The true origin of the PRE is not an exact science; what is known is that in the pre-Roman era, there were already references to horses in what is today known as Spain. Roman authors such as Plutarch, Pliny the Old and Seneca spoke of the Hispanic horse as a beautiful, docile, arrogant and brave horse, ideal for war and for the sports that were carried out in the circuses at that time. During the reign of King Philip II, the equine realm of his Kingdom was organized, laying down the final bases so that the PRE was able to reach its peak during subsequent years. This was possible with the creation of the Royal Stables in Cordoba, where he gathered together the best stallions and mares from all the provinces bordering the Guadalquivir River, which at that time, were the most productive in the breeding of horses. Thus, the Royal Stud Farm was created, which after time became known as the National Stud Farm. A multitude of horses were exported to the American continents; these horses played a decisive role on its exploration, and were the origin and basis for most of the breeds that have subsequently been bred in America. In Europe, Spain was enjoying its Golden Age. At that time, the most treasured gift from a Spanish monarch was one of the nation’s magnificent horses. Spanish horses soon earned repute and were decisive in the birth of many Central European breeds. Breeds such as the Lipizzaner, Lusitano, Paso Fino and the Central European Warmbloods all owe their ancestry to the PRE. There are currently about 170,000 PRE horses throughout the whole world, bred in more than 60 countries.

The Clun Forest is an ‘easy care’ sheep breed ideal for both small holders and commercial breeders alike. It is resistant to disease, long lived and hardy with good mothering traits and particularly free from lambing complications. It is happy to live in hot and cold climates, 1500 feet above sea level or on rich lowlands. Whether producing pure bred, Down or Mule cross lambs, the progeny is early maturing making 16 to 20 kgs from 12 to 17 weeks old and up to 29kg under a year old. The wool is fine and used for knitting and making futons. The meat should be lean and tasty. The striking and usual appearance of the Clun Forest makes it an attractive prospect for the show ring.

The Drenthe Heath is the oldest sheep breed of the Western Europe continent. Approximately 4000 BC the first Drenthe Heath sheep came to Drenthe (a province in the northeast Netherlands). They probably came with emigrants from France. Breed description The Drenthe Heath is multicoloured black, red, brown and white, with wool being mostly white, while the head is reddish-brown and black. Animals may also be spotted. Both sexes have horns, but there is a rare occurrence of polled animals. The Drenthe Heath can easily live on poor heathland. The Drenthe Heath is managed with transhumance with local grazing throughout the year. Ewes typically produce one lamb at a time. The Drenthe Heath is mainly used for conservation grazing and meat, although wool products are also valuable. www.drentsheideschaap.nl

In more fertile regions of Drenthe a more productive breed was kept: the Schoonebeek Heath sheep. The Schoonebeek turned out to be economically more interesting than old heath sheep breeds by the time fertilizers were introduced. Because of the fertilizers, the poor heathland became more fertile and the Schoonebeek is more productive than the old heath sheep breeds, because it is slightly bigger and a well-meated sheep. However, by now, the Schoonebeek is displaced by other modern breeds that are again more productive. Breed description The Schoonebeek is multicoloured, black, brown, yellow and white, with black spots including on the head. They may be unicoloured brownish black as well. They have a long tail and are polled. The Schoonebeek is managed by transhumance, adapted to extensive conditions, with total grazing. Historically, the Schoonebeek were used for the management of heath fields and production of manure. Now, the breed is mainly used for conservation grazing, although meat and wool products are also valuable. In comparison to the Dutch Texel the Schoonebeek is higher in wool fibre thickness. www.drentsheideschaap.nl

The Texel Sheep is a medium-sized sheep. An adult ram weighs approximately 95 kilos and stands at about 70 centimetres at the withers. A mature ewe weighs 75 kilos on average and stands 68 centimetres at the withers. The Texel Sheep is a medium sized sheep, that lambs once a year. Adult ewes usually birth and suckle two lambs per litter. Ewes can have their first litter at 12 months. The Texel Sheep is of very good meat quality, with excellent fat deposition. A Texel Sheep is large-framed, has a solid square stance and looks bigger than its actual size. Its head is characteristic and well-proportioned with a straight nasal bridge and a wide mouth. The head is covered with fine white hair, in contrast to the black nose. Its neck is long and in proportion. The body has pronounced muscling with well-developed loins and thighs. The forehand, middle and hind quarters are evenly proportioned. The Texel Sheep’s forehand is broad and deep, with well-positioned and reasonably long shoulders and a breastbone extending sufficiently to the front. Its middle piece is long and broad with sufficient depth in the ribs and broad, strong loins. The hindquarters are broad, while the croup is long and lightly sloped. The legs have a delicate structure, are dry and powerful, and are positioned correctly when walking or standing. Its wool is fine, dense and doesn’t contain excess lanolin. The rump is covered in a white coat. Both head and legs aren’t covered with wool but with fine white hair. The tail is thin and of appropriate length.  HISTORY  Origins of the Texel Sheep  The Texel Sheep was bred over a hundred years ago as a crossbreed from indigenous marsh sheep and several British breeds, such as Leicester, Wensleydale and Lincoln. This resulted in a large, fast-growing and woolly sheep. Through effective selection, this breed of sheep has become the most heavily muscled meat sheep in the world. The Texel Sheep is a breed in which excellent carcass quality and great prolific qualities come together.  The Netherlands has a long history of sheep farming. Approximately 1.5 million sheep are kept on about 20,000 farms. Specialist sheep farms have over 300 ewes. Most sheep are held in dairy farms as a secondary activity, with ewes lambing in spring. Breeding, reproduction and meat farming is mainly integrated in the company’s activities. Sheep are mainly kept for meat production. The profitability of sheep farming is determined by lamb production, growth rate and meat quality.  Over the past few decades, sheep farmers have invested a lot of money in research on increasing the profitability of their businesses. By using rams with superior genetic traits, great progress has been made in further improving the functional exterior features and carcass composition. Where in the past the emphasis was on meat and wool production, the main goal of today is the sales of slaughter lambs of a consistent, high quality.
